# TcPOU File Format

## XML Structure

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<TcPlcObject Version="1.1.0.1" ProductVersion="3.1.4024.15">
  <POU Name="FB_Example" Id="{GUID}" SpecialFunc="None">
    <Declaration><![CDATA[
FUNCTION_BLOCK FB_Example
VAR_INPUT
    bEnable : BOOL;
END_VAR
]]></Declaration>
    <Implementation>
      <ST><![CDATA[
// Implementation code here
]]></ST>
    </Implementation>
  </POU>
</TcPlcObject>
```

## GUID Rules

Every XML element with an `Id` attribute requires a GUID. GUIDs are the primary identity mechanism for TwinCAT objects — they link POUs, methods, properties, and actions across the solution.

### Format

Standard UUID v4, lowercase hex with hyphens, wrapped in curly braces:

```
Id="{a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890}"
```

- 8-4-4-4-12 hex digits: `{xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx}`
- Lowercase letters: `{a1b2...}` not `{A1B2...}`
- Always include curly braces in the XML attribute value

### Generation

Generate a fresh random GUID for each new element. Methods:
- PowerShell: `[guid]::NewGuid().ToString('D')` then wrap in `{}`
- Python: `import uuid; f'{{{uuid.uuid4()}}}'`

### Uniqueness scope

Every GUID must be **unique across the entire PLC project** (all `.TcPOU`, `.TcIO`, `.TcDUT`, `.TcGVL` files combined). Two different elements must never share the same GUID, even across different files.

### GUID count per element

| Element | GUIDs needed | Id locations |
|---------|:------------:|--------------|
| POU (FB / Function / Program) | 1 | `<POU Id="...">` |
| Method | 1 | `<Method Id="...">` |
| Action | 1 | `<Action Id="...">` |
| Property | 3 | `<Property Id="...">` + `<Get Id="...">` + `<Set Id="...">` |
| Property (read-only, no Set) | 2 | `<Property Id="...">` + `<Get Id="...">` |
| DUT (Struct / Enum / Union) | 1 | `<DUT Id="...">` |
| GVL | 1 | `<GVL Id="...">` |

### Rules

- **Never reuse** a GUID from another element — always generate fresh
- **Never change** an existing GUID when editing code — GUIDs are stable identifiers
- **Never omit** the `Id` attribute — TwinCAT requires it on every POU/Method/Property/Action/DUT/GVL element
- **Never copy-paste** a file without replacing ALL GUIDs with fresh ones

## Critical Rules

1. **Edit ONLY inside `<![CDATA[...]]>` sections** — never touch XML tags
2. **Name attribute MUST match** the FUNCTION_BLOCK/FUNCTION/PROGRAM name inside CDATA
3. **SpecialFunc** is usually `"None"`. Only `"FB_init"`, `"FB_reinit"`, `"FB_exit"` for special cases.
4. **Preserve existing GUIDs** when editing — never change them

## Methods (inside POU, after `</Implementation>`)

```xml
    <Method Name="MethodName" Id="{DIFFERENT-GUID}">
      <Declaration><![CDATA[
METHOD MethodName : BOOL
VAR_INPUT
    nParam : INT;
END_VAR
]]></Declaration>
      <Implementation>
        <ST><![CDATA[
MethodName := TRUE;
]]></ST>
      </Implementation>
    </Method>
```

Each method needs its **OWN unique GUID**, different from the POU's GUID.

## Properties (inside POU)

```xml
    <Property Name="PropName" Id="{UNIQUE-GUID}">
      <Declaration><![CDATA[
PROPERTY PropName : INT
]]></Declaration>
      <Get Name="Get" Id="{UNIQUE-GUID}">
        <Declaration><![CDATA[VAR END_VAR]]></Declaration>
        <Implementation>
          <ST><![CDATA[PropName := _nValue;]]></ST>
        </Implementation>
      </Get>
      <Set Name="Set" Id="{UNIQUE-GUID}">
        <Declaration><![CDATA[VAR END_VAR]]></Declaration>
        <Implementation>
          <ST><![CDATA[_nValue := PropName;]]></ST>
        </Implementation>
      </Set>
    </Property>
```

Property + Get + Set = 3 separate GUIDs needed.

## Actions (inside POU, after `</Implementation>`)

```xml
    <Action Name="A_HandleError" Id="{UNIQUE-GUID}">
      <Implementation>
        <ST><![CDATA[
nErrorCounter := nErrorCounter + 1;
bError        := TRUE;
]]></ST>
      </Implementation>
    </Action>
```

Rules:
- Each action needs its **OWN unique GUID**
- Actions have **no** `<Declaration>` section (unlike methods)
- Actions are **not registered separately** in .plcproj
- Call via `A_HandleError();` inside the FB's cyclic code
- Naming: `A_[Verb][Object]` — e.g. `A_CalculatePower`, `A_HandleFailsafe`

## POU Types

- `FUNCTION_BLOCK FB_Name` - stateful, instantiated
- `FUNCTION F_Name : ReturnType` - stateless, direct call
- `PROGRAM MAIN` - entry point, called by task
